{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15900"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.32,0.09,0.17,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63050"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2038"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"4667"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43600"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63050"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic reporting an eight-month history of pain and inability to have penetrative sexual intercourse. She has never been able to achieve penetrative intercourse or use tampons. She states that her partner is very supportive and that they have tried increasing lubrication and foreplay with no significant improvement in the pain. She has began to feel anxious about the anticipated pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill. She has never experienced sexual abuse or trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is visibly anxious during the attempted gynaecological examination, and insertion of a speculum is not possible due to pain and tightening of the vaginal muscles, despite adequate lubrication. External genitalia appear normal with no signs of infection, inflammation, or dermatological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cognitive behavioural therapy","Pelvic floor physiotherapy","Topical lidocaine gel","Vaginal dilators","Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of vaginismus, a condition where pelvic floor muscle spasm makes penetration difficult or impossible. The inability to use tampons and difficulty with gynaecological examination are characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic floor physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. A trained physiotherapist can help the patient identify and learn to relax their pelvic floor muscles, which is fundamental to successful treatment. They can also teach techniques for muscle control and relaxation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in addressing anxiety and fear associated with penetration, but is typically introduced after initial physiotherapy has helped establish some physical control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal dilators\u003C/strong\u003E are an important part of treatment but are usually introduced gradually under the guidance of a physiotherapist or specialist, not as a first-line intervention. Use of dilators without guidance around muscle relaxation may cause further pain and anxiety, leading to hesitation around future treatment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical lidocaine gel\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary relief but does not address the underlying muscle dysfunction and anxiety. It should not be used as a first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective serotonin reuptake inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if there is significant associated anxiety or depression, but it is not the first-line treatment for vaginismus. The focus should be on addressing the physical aspects of the condition initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of vaginismus typically requires a multidisciplinary approach. After establishing pelvic floor control through physiotherapy, other interventions such as dilators, psychological support, and sometimes medication can be introduced as needed. Partner involvement and education are also important components of successful treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vaginismus is characterised by pelvic floor muscle spasm causing pain and difficulty with penetration.","A thorough history and examination is essential to differentiate vaginismus from other causes of dyspareunia.","Management of vaginismus involves a multidisciplinary approach including pelvic floor physiotherapy and psychological support."],"references":["Ter Kuile MM, Melles R, de Groot HE, Tuijnman-Raasveld CC, van Lankveld JJDM. Therapist-aided exposure for women with lifelong vaginismus: A randomized waiting-list control trial of efficacy. Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology. 2013 Dec;81(6):1127\u201336. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24060195/","Wallace SL, Miller LD, Mishra K. Pelvic floor physical therapy in the treatment of pelvic floor dysfunction in women. Curr Opin Obstet Gynecol. 2019 Dec;31(6):485-493. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31609735/","I\u015f\u0131k C, Aslan E. The effects of sexual counseling and pelvic floor relaxation on sexual functions in women receiving vaginismus treatment: a randomized controlled study. Int Urogynecol J. 2023 Mar;34(3):683-692. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35501569/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T21:11:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T21:12:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63050"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"se